comment:
October 15th, 2021, 8pm, Friday evening:
I was sitting on the couch as usual, ready to end the week with a relaxed movie night as suddenly for whatever reason the youtube algorithm proposed me to click a music video by Amy Winehouse. 

Of course by that time I was aware of her, some famous singer, same age as me, drug addict, who shouted out loud she would never go to rehab and finally died at young age. For sure I've known some of her songs from the radio as well, but actually didn¬¥t see any reason at all to further approach her music. 

Before choosing the movie for the night I anyway clicked on that proposed video, just like clicking on thousands of others for no particular purpose.

That Friday movie night ended on Saturday morning, 2am, after watching 6 hours in a row one Amy Winehouse video after the other. I have never had such a mind-blowing experience related to music in my entire life. I can truly say I got addicted that day. 


Thank you so much for enriching my life, Amy! üíö

comment: God. I can really feel her emotions in this. She‚Äôs a smiling girl outside where everyone can see her physically‚Ä¶ but that girl inside is just in a fetal position‚Ä¶ staring off blankly slowly crying‚Ä¶. Just makes you want to hug the fuck out of her and treat her the way she wants to be loved and treated unconditionally.. such a broken soul‚Ä¶ I would have loved to have smoked a bowl of weed with her.. just chill on our instruments and just talk about how fucked up life was.. just to relate and not only let her know that she‚Äôs not alone.. but that none of us were alone. This woman would walk on the side of a fucking sidewalk and just casually talk amongst her friends or people who said hey to her. She had a posh accent and was really just like the rest of us who we consider normal and not celebrities. Even had a wicked sense of humor ‚ò∫Ô∏è‚Ä¶ it sucks she‚Äôs gone cause I really feel her at this phase in my life right now‚Ä¶ it‚Äôs so relatable and raw emotion‚Ä¶. comment:
I might be opening myself up to some heat here, so please just bear in mind that I‚Äôm simply expressing an opinion of music and have no wish to disrespect the dead.
 With that said, during Amy Winehouse‚Äôs career there was not one single of hers I heard on the radio that I enjoyed. I can‚Äôt tell you why but I just didn‚Äôt enjoy them at all.
 HOWEVER, having come here from a video interview with Bill Bailey who was asked which song he can‚Äôt listen to, and he said he can‚Äôt hear this song without crying, I have to admit I can see where he‚Äôs coming from.
 This song is (again, in my personal opinion) infinitely better than her singles, and I remember hearing a song of hers in my first job (although I couldn‚Äôt tell you the name of it) that damn near lulled me to sleep because it was so soulful, so chilled, so soothing. It was beautiful and I really wish I knew what it was called.

Makes me want to look into her back catalogue and see what other absolute gems I‚Äôve missed.

Edit: I‚Äôve since discovered that this was a single but didn‚Äôt chart as well as the ones I remember, which is likely why I never heard it.

comment:
Love, between men and women, is almost invariably a losing game, as all games are. Evermore of one as the expectation of both are evermore unrealistic. Genuine friendship and natural respect can be gained. However, if the people involved, seriously expect the relationship to be anything notably more than a devotion to the procreation and nurturing of children then best not to start in the first place.
Love is the answer all right. But not the romantic type, indeed if it has anything to do with having sex, then it is not love, you only think it is. We look for love in the wrong places, give it to the wrong people, for the wrong reasons and wonder why we lose what we never had in the first place.

comment:
I remember travelling into London with my mum and brother when I was about 14 or 15 years old. When we got into London, not far from islington/highbury area, the traffic was slow but flowing with a stop start rhythm. As we were gradually edging towards the front of a queue that was caused by a set of traffic lights, a beautiful girl that was sitting and waiting at a bus stop to the left of me caught my eye. I couldn't help but stare at her as she sat there and gaze towards the sky, in her own world. Looking at her I could see that her carefree head was in the clouds just watching the day go past. 

She then turned her head and noticed me staring at her, we made eye contact. As we paused in that brief but beautiful moment, eyes locked looking at one another, we shared a beautiful subtle smile before breaking into a full on contagious beaming smile, as if we were good friends sharing a private joke and all the passersby were none the wiser.

I thought "wow look how beautiful she is and what a gorgeous smile" and then blushingly I turned my gaze away, not wanting to make it awkward for myself nor her.

Then I thought to myself "Hold on! Was that?!"

I snapped my neck back and realised, Yes! it was indeed Amy Winehouse! She started laughing realising that I had processed, computed and only just clocked on. 

I exclaimed to my brother "look!! that's Amy Winehouse there!"  He was more focused on the road and the lights up ahead as they began to change green he didnt believe me anyway.  

As the car started moving I quickly put my windows down and shouted "AMY!!" She looked and was laughing even harder and then I knew without doubt it was her.

The cars moved off and my moment with her had passed.

I still think of that moment, especially when I go into London, as I usually go past the exact same spot. I think what if I would have got out the car and just took my shot at striking a conversation with her. Just to connect with another human and interact before going on about our days and lives. 

She had a beautiful smile. And I can still picture her in that moment.

comment: You know, I often listen to Back To Black and did so today, 10/1/20, which prompted this commentary...my god, this album has been out 14 years now and she's been gone 9 years! Love Is A Losing Game is, in my opinion, the absolute BEST song on this work and that is saying something...she was an absolute genius but seriously flawed and this song, probably more so among most of her catalogue, portrays these failings best...written at an amazingly young of 23, it nevertheless projects a profoundly adult experience with love lost and hurt all within a magical musical cacophony. Indeed, I virtually listened to this in my entire drive from Stephenville, Texas to Waco, Texas in early 2011 when going to my daughter's Senior Volleyball game (about 2 hours)...I couldn't get enough!!! When she died in July of that year, I really wasn't sad, I was more frustrated...was I the only one who saw this coming?!?!? Anyway, just count me among the millions who miss her amazing talent and have ardent memories of her music...

author: Maria S'

comment: The quiet resignation of this song haunts me. As a 50+ yr old (boomer, yeah) the most relevant band in my teen years was Joy Division, and I can sense a link between Amy's album Back To Black and JD's 'Closer'. The same sort of terrible resignation to fate haunts it, as if the singer's fate is alrready sealed, she was just appointed to it without having a choice. I also think Amy was basically a nice woman, it comes across in her interviews. I recall watching clips of her making cups of tea for journos and giving them jaffa cakes outside her house in Camden. Little things like that stay with me. It's just too bad. Maybe the best pop musicians have to live on the edge and burn out, I dunno. I couldn't do that myself, but then again I'll never write songs like this, so I really don't know what to say except RIP, and thank you for this music that makes me feel alive.

comment: Last night I watched the documentary on her life. At all times and well knowing how it all ended, I waited for a miracle. I hoped it was all fiction. And as it came to the end and I was exchanging impressions with my husband, I broke into tears. She was a victim of different events and how things played out in her life. I cried for her and the young force of life she was and how a series of poorly made decisions lead to her end. It breaks my heart and I still can't get used to the fact that she's gone.

comment:
So beautiful, this song.  Definitely a product of the crossroads.  The contract.  

Many artists have been there and signed their souls away for the power of music.  This song is so powerful and in the end, the entity responsible came to claim its payment in the form of Amy's life.

Like Jim Morrison, Janice Joplin, Chester Bennington, Jimmy Hendrix and so many other young artists, I believe that they knew their fates.  They made their decisions at the crossroads.

comment: I agree with Melissa Evans as a matter of fact I just made this same exact comment to my daughter! It's as if her soul came back from a different time to finish  writing the last songs of the sixties the age of Aquarius. I want to add though that I now believe Amy was a Twin Flame! She even says so in this very song. "For you I was a Flame" This she wrote before there were any Twin Flame help videos on you tube. The way her love story played out, the intensity of her love for this guy, the tortured nature of the connection the fact that she loved him in spite of every thing unconditionally all of it! Maybe if she had access to the information things would have been different. All and all I think she did complete her mission she left us these songs......she left us her love story! Thank you Amy where ever you are the Gods are probably rejoicing happy that you are home! To Twin Flames  and Amy Fans every where Love & Light!

comment: Okay guys tell me if you guys get this....... Ok I truly feel like God was actually giving us a taste and an actual feel of what REAL music was like in the 60s you know the feelings you get when you listen to Janis Joplin or Jimi Hendrix. I genuinely feel like who Amy was as a person, the way she dressed, how much pain she had in her voice when she sang, the fact that she didn't even want  to be so famous she just wanted to write music, and it's crazy but even the way she passed away it's such a 60s and 70s style. I always tell myself when you hear her music it doesn't sound like a song from this generation it sounds like a timeless classic from 1960 or something. There will never be another like Amy Winehouse but she has opened a door for so many other artists like Lana Del Ray and Adele  and I just want to thank you God for letting us feel that real, raw,painful deep 60s feel of music from Amy one last time that we can keep forever and I miss her so much. We love you Amy. R.I.P.

comment: It's really hard for me to listen to Amy's music without a tear falling. My mom raised me on Amy winehouse's music, and whenever she picked me up from school or we went on a roadtrip,  one of Amy's albums would be playing. I think her death was more death by media. Sure, she overdosed on drugs, but the cameras were constantly in her face, watching her every move. There was so much pressure on her. Just imagine if she had gotten older and other artists did musical tributes to her like they do for people like Stevie Wonder a d Diana Ross! And I still remember that day my mom n took it so hard that Amy had passed away. When Amy died, a part of my childhood died with her.

comment: Every now and then a voice comes along that makes your heart beat faster as you listen, in fact you are forced to sit up and listen, and then you marvel, how can a voice sound that great, that soulful? And you know that the remarkable feeling Amy instils in you is just going to be with you until you die. This is the magical power that Amy had over us, we that loved her and that sweet husky, ethereal, special voice. I will never cease to wonder at how she used to make me feel, how she touched me deeply, and how I lost something in my life when she passed away. I know that I'm not the only one that feels this way. Such a loss, such a special and rare thing was Amy Winehouse.

comment:
'A poem for Amy'



EMERALD EYES
¬†
¬†
¬†
Your eyes speak without words ; reveling the
Deep secrets of overwhelming pain.. I
Have seen this blank stare within
The stars above ; they hold the key to
Many a life's mystery.. If I were granted but¬†just
One wish I would spend it on you and
Set you free from this sorrow.. you
Carry the soul of ten thousand years and
The heart reserved for a child,
Pure, clean, untainted.. your
Emerald eyes hold many a secret like
The ancient scroll before you.. they are the
Windows to your soul reveling your deepest
Sorrow and emotion., the savior awaits you with
Open arms.. as time draws near I
Close these eyes for the last time to
Enter a new beginning.. no more pain, no
More suffering or sorrow to consume me; I
Am now far from the world I once new, my
Mission now complete ; I
Am at last one with peace.. for
These emerald eyes are no longer in pain..
¬†
¬†
¬† - Ken Riccio original poems ¬©

comment: Every now and then a voice comes along that makes your heart beat faster and you have to sit up and listen to it, you just have to and then you marvel, astounded that anyone could sing like that. And you know that the remarkable feeling she instils in you is just going to be with you until you die, you won't be able to get this sound out of your mind. This is the magical power that Amy had over us, we that loved her along with that sweet husky ethereal special voice she had. I will never cease to wonder at how she used to make me feel the moment one of her songs came on the radio or on the TV. How she touched me deeply, and how I lost something in my life when she passed away. I know that I'm not the only one that feels this way. Such a loss, such a special and rare thing was Amy Winehouse. Will we ever hear such a rare and touching voice as hers gain? Tragic Magic, I miss you Amy, so much.

comment:
Tragically, but not without poetic value, Amy seemed to self-author her own obituary in the course of her short life. The video to this song is so posthumously postured, almost as if it were being sung by a woman who had resigned herself to the inevitability of her fate. The song, sung as it were, from beyond the grave. 

Truly gifted. A fully formed genius. She bore truth, beauty & honesty on her young shoulders. Perhaps a burden too great for her. Sometimes, genius can't contain itself.

Rest.
